message.content:
The President of the United States in 1996 was Bill Clinton, who served as the 42nd President from January 20, 1993, to January 20, 2001. He was a member of the Democratic Party and his vice president during this time was Al Gore.

During his presidency, Clinton faced various domestic and international challenges, including economic growth, healthcare reform, and foreign policy issues. In 1996, he won re-election against Republican nominee Bob Dole and Reform Party candidate Ross Perot.
